&gt; What is the idiom for choosing a single implementation from multiple
&gt; available implementations?

It makes perfect sense to have multiple implementations at the same time.

Just as an example:

    interface ImageFilter {
        String getName();
        String getDescription();
        String getUsage();
        List&lt;Parameter&gt; getParameters();
        Image apply(Image image, List&lt;Parameters&gt; parameters);
    }

Now your program (service, library, ...) can work with any type of image filter even if it is installed after your program.

&gt; As far as I can tell, the iteration order

You just have to iterate to know what implementations are available, but you don&#39;t have to use them immediately. In the image filter example, you would iterate to show them in a selector (eg. using `getName`) and the user would select one to apply (`apply`), see detailed information (`getDescription`), usage, parameters, ...

But these are only examples, there are many other possible scenarios (eg. for a calculation, you could launch all the implementations in parallel and see which one ends before, or take the one that has reached the best accuracy, ... or you can base the choice of an implementation on certain code annotations, ...).

On the other hand, write `META-INF/services` is only one way to inject the available implementations, see [Creating Extensible Applications][1] for detailed information.


  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/ext/basics/spi.html

