You can use `rxjs` `pipe` operator to combine `take` and `interval` as

    counter: number = 0;
    items: string[] = [&quot;one&quot;, &quot;tow&quot;, &quot;three&quot;, &quot;four&quot;];
    
      ngOnInit() {
        interval(2000)
          .pipe(take(this.items.length))
          .subscribe(res =&gt; {
            console.log(console.log(this.items[this.counter++]));
          });
      }

**Edit:** You need to create an Observable stream using `Observable.create` where you can use `setInterval` in create observables at regular intervals and at the end, you can mark it as complete.

Once subscribed, we would have separate methods executed once a new value is emitted and once the observable is marked complete

    obs: Observable&lt;any&gt;;
    counter: number = 0;
    items: string[] = [&quot;one&quot;, &quot;two&quot;, &quot;three&quot;, &quot;four&quot;];

  

    ngOnInit() {
        this.obs = Observable.create(observer =&gt; {
          let intervalID = setInterval(() =&gt; {
            observer.next(this.items[this.counter++]);
            if (this.counter &gt;= this.items.length) {
              clearInterval(intervalID);
              observer.complete();
            }
          }, 1000);
        });
    
        this.obs.subscribe(
          res =&gt; {
            console.log(res);
          },
          err =&gt; {
            console.log(`Error: ${err}`);
          },
          () =&gt; {
            console.log(&quot;complete&quot;);
          }
        );
      }

Stackblitz at: https://stackblitz.com/edit/angular-regular-interval-observables-with-complete

You can use `merge` with a timer and ignore the output of said timer:

```ts
import { of, from, timer } from &#39;rxjs&#39;
import { concatMap, merge, ignoreElements, tap, toArray } from &#39;rxjs/operators&#39;

const documents = [
  {
    &#39;documentId&#39;: 1,
    &#39;documentName&#39;: &#39;DocName1&#39;
  },
  {
    &#39;documentId&#39;: 2,
    &#39;documentName&#39;: &#39;DocName2&#39;
  },
];

function saveDocumentService(document) {
  document[&#39;someAnotherData&#39;] = &#39;123&#39;;
  return of(document)
}
from(documents)
  .pipe(
    concatMap(url =&gt; saveDocumentService(url).pipe(
      tap(res =&gt; console.log(&#39;Saved document...&#39;)),
      merge(timer(1000).pipe(ignoreElements()))
    )),
    toArray(),
  )
  .subscribe(documents =&gt; {
    console.log(&#39;Sub:&#39;, documents)
  })
```

